{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.25,0.01,0.54,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87977"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1044"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"3487"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44838"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with concerns about frequent infections. He has had five episodes of otitis media and one episodes of pneumonia requiring antibiotics in the past year. He also experiences intermittent loose stools and abdominal pain. He was born at term and has met all developmental milestones. His immunisations are up to date. He has no other medical conditions and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His height and weight plot along the 25th percentile. Examination of his ears, throat, chest and abdomen is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgA \u0026lt;0.07 g/L (0.4-2.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EIgG 10.2 g/L (5.0-13.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EIgM 1.1 g/L (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prophylactic antibiotics","Monthly intravenous immunoglobulin infusions","Bone marrow transplantation","Screening for coeliac disease","No further action required"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with selective IgA deficiency, including recurrent respiratory tract infections and gastrointestinal symptoms. The diagnosis is confirmed by the very low IgA level with normal IgG and IgM levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening for coeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as there is a strong association between IgA deficiency and autoimmune conditions, particularly coeliac disease. The patient\u0027s gastrointestinal symptoms and growth parameters warrant investigation. It\u0027s important to note that standard coeliac screening using IgA-based tests will be falsely negative, so IgG-based testing should be used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonthly intravenous immunoglobulin infusions\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in isolated IgA deficiency. These infusions contain very little IgA, and most patients with selective IgA deficiency maintain adequate immunity through other mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in cases with frequent severe infections, but given this patient is otherwise well, they are not necessary as first-line management. The focus should be on prompt treatment of infections when they occur. Severe infections include \u0026gt;8 otitis media per year, \u0026gt;2 episodes of pneumonia, and sepsis requiring hospitalisation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E would be an extremely aggressive approach that is not indicated for selective IgA deficiency, which generally has a good prognosis and does not significantly impact life expectancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the need to monitor for associated conditions and provide appropriate anticipatory guidance. The patient requires ongoing follow-up to monitor for complications and associated conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should focus on education about infection prevention, prompt treatment of infections when they occur, and screening for associated conditions. Patients should also be advised about the theoretical risk of transfusion reactions and the need to inform healthcare providers about their IgA deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selective IgA deficiency is the most common primary immunodeficiency, often presenting with recurrent respiratory and gastrointestinal infections.","IgA deficiency is associated with an increased risk of autoimmune conditions, particularly coeliac disease.","Most patients with IgA deficiency do not require specific treatment beyond prompt management of infections and screening for associated conditions."],"references":["Koenen MH, van Montfrans JM, Sanders EAM, Bogaert D, Verhagen LM. Immunoglobulin A deficiency in children, an undervalued clinical issue. Clin Immunol. 2019 Dec;209:108293. doi: 10.1016/j.clim.2019.108293. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31678364."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87977"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87977"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T10:52:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T10:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attribut